data.body:
- VSCode Version: 1.5.3
- OS Version: Ubuntu Linux

Steps to Reproduce:
1. create a `foo.ts` with contents like:

``` js
import * as ts from 'typescript';

ts.SyntaxKind;
```
1. create a `tsconfig.json` with contents like this.  (this is what "tsc --init" produces with additional `baseUrl` and `paths` properties.)

``` js
{
    "compilerOptions": {
        "module": "commonjs",
        "target": "es5",
        "noImplicitAny": false,
        "sourceMap": false,
        "baseUrl": ".",
        "paths": {
            "typescript": [
                "/path/to/typescript/source/typescript.d.ts"
            ]
        }
    },
    "exclude": [
        "node_modules"
    ]
}
```
1. hover on the "ts" symbol and notice it takes six seconds to resolve.  if it's fast, ctl-click on it once, then close the tab, and then hover it again.

Note: /path/to/typescript/source/typescript.d.ts in my case is a very deep path into a network filesystem that is decently fast (it caches locally) but slower than an SSD.

The trace (from the `"typescript.tsserver.trace": "verbose"` setting) shows six seconds for the response to come back.

```
[Trace - 9:40:22 AM] Sending request: quickinfo (22). Response expected: yes. Current queue length: 0
Arguments: {
    "file": "/.../t/foo.ts",
    "line": 1,
    "offset": 14
}
[Trace - 9:40:28 AM] Response received: quickinfo (22). Request took 5820 ms. Success: true 
Result: {
    "kind": "alias",
    "kindModifiers": "",
    "start": {
        "line": 1,
        "offset": 13
    },
    "end": {
        "line": 1,
        "offset": 15
    },
    "displayString": "import ts",
    "documentation": ""
}
```

I used `strace` to trace the file system accesses of the tsserver subprocess and it seems to be looking at hundreds of paths, maybe even stuck in a loop.  Unfortunately the log contains filenames that work probably doesn't want me to publish on a bug tracker, otherwise I'd publish it here.

But it looks like it's looking for node_modules/ and files like package.json, index.d.ts, typescripts.tsx, and so on, for every possible directory mentioned in that `paths` variable, despite us telling it where exactly to look.

Specifying a filename in 'paths' seems consistent with the module documentation written here:

http://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/module-resolution.html

All our global actions contributed from the workbench need to have exactly 2 arguments: ID and label. This makes it hard to contribute parameterized actions that take a context as argument (imagine you have 1 base class of action to toggle viewlets and you want to pass in the viewlet ID).

Tracing down the code it ends up in https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/src/vs/platform/actions/common/actions.ts#L176 where we have `IConstructorSignature2<string, string, Action>`

I am not really sure who added this code to begin with but cc'ing some folks ( @joaomoreno @alexandrudima @jrieken ).

My proposal would be that you can pass in the `SyncDescriptor<Action>` into the `ctor` so that you can create any kind of descriptor before hand:

``` typescript
export class SyncActionDescriptor {...
   constructor(descriptor: SyncDescriptor0<Action>, id: string, label: string, keybindings?: IKeybindings, keybindingContext?: ContextKeyExpr, keybindingWeight?: number);
   constructor(ctor: IConstructorSignature2<string, string, Action>, id: string, label: string, keybindings?: IKeybindings, keybindingContext?: ContextKeyExpr, keybindingWeight?: number);
   constructor(arg1: any, id: string, label: string, keybindings?: IKeybindings, keybindingContext?: ContextKeyExpr, keybindingWeight?: number) {
    this._id = id;
    this._label = label;
    this._keybindings = keybindings;
    this._keybindingContext = keybindingContext;
    this._keybindingWeight = keybindingWeight;
    this._descriptor = arg1 instanceof SyncDescriptor ? <any>arg1 : createSyncDescriptor(arg1, this._id, this._label);
}
```

Challenging part is that both `SyncDescriptor0` and `IConstructorSignature2` are interfaces so I cannot really do an instanceof check.

Ideas?
